<TITLE> Dutch to study access passes after security alert </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 AMSTERDAM, March 12 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - The Dutch intelligence service AIVD will examine the security of access passes for buildings following fears the cards could be duplicated easily, the Interior Ministry said on Tuesday. Researchers at Radboud University in the eastern town of Nijmegen said they had found a serious weakness in the security of the "Mifare Classic" chip used in an estimated 1 billion passes worldwide. The Interior Ministry said it was ready to take extra security measures. "It has to be assumed that once the details of the university's study become public, the possibility for abuse will have such a low threshold that additional measures are necessary to maintain the level of security," the ministry said. The chip's security was called into question last December when a presentation at a conference of hacker group Chaos Computer Club (CCC) pointed to design weaknesses. "We are taking these claims very seriously and are investigating them," NXP, maker of the Mifare Classic chip, said in a stateme
